draw((2,5)--(3,5),Arrow);
label("$x^\circ$",(0.1,4));
draw((3,5)--(4,5),Arrow);
label("$115^\circ$",(0,0),NE);
label("$75^\circ$",(8,5),SW);
label("$105^\circ$",(6.5,0),E);
[/asy] ||| Since \( AB \) is parallel to \( DC \), we can say that \( \angle ACB = 180^{\circ} - 105^{\circ} = 75^{\circ} \). Then in triangle \( ABC \), we have: 
\begin{align*}
\angle BAC &= 180^{\circ} - \angle ABC - \angle ACB \\
&= 180^{\circ} - 75^{\circ} - 75^{\circ} \\
&= 30^{\circ}.
\end{align*} 
So \( \angle ACD \) should also be \( 30^{\circ} \). In triangle \( ADC \), we can calculate: 
\begin{align*}
\angle DAC &= 180^{\circ} - \angle ADC - \angle ACD \\
&= 180^{\circ} - 115^{\circ} - 30^{\circ} \\
&= 35^{\circ}.
\end{align*}  
Therefore, the value of \( x \) is \( \boxed{35} \).

