label("B",(8,4),N);
label("P",(4,4),N);
label("A",(0,4),N);
[/asy] ||| First, let's consider triangles that form right angles at points P and Q. Since points A, B, C, and D should not be used in this case, we can't form any right triangles this way. Therefore, the only possible triangles would involve the corners of rectangle ABCD. For each corner (A, B, C, D), we can draw one triangle with both legs on the sides of the rectangle, but it's only really two triangles: ABQ and CDQ. Thus, we only get 4 right triangles. \n\nNext, each of the triangles AQP and BQP can be drawn, giving us 2 more right triangles. Adding them up gives us a total of 6 right triangles, which is clearly wrong since we missed several triangles. Therefore, the answer appears to be too low: \boxed{6}.

