If $\angle A=20^\circ$ and $\angle AFG=\angle AGF,$ then how many degrees is $\angle B+\angle D?$ [asy]
/* AMC8 2000 #24 Problem */
pair A=(0,80), B=(46,108), C=(100,80), D=(54,18), E=(19,0);
draw(A--C--E--B--D--cycle);
label("$A$", A, W);
label("$B$ ", B, N);
label("$C$", shift(7,0)*C);
label("$D$", D, SE);
label("$E$", E, SW);
label("$F$", (23,43));
label("$G$", (35, 86));
[/asy] ||| Since \angle AFG=\angle AGF and we know \angle A=20^\circ, we can write: \angle GAF + \angle AFG + \angle AGF = 180^\circ. So we have: 20^\circ + 2(\angle AFG) = 180^\circ. This means 2(\angle AFG) = 160^\circ, and hence \angle AFG = 80^\circ. Therefore, if we find that \angle BFD = 80^\circ, then by the triangle angle sum property in triangle BFD, we can conclude that \angle B + \angle D = 80^\circ. Therefore, the answer is \boxed{80^\circ}.

